== A Note Before You Begin


Not every question here will apply to your story. Skip what doesn't serve you.


If religion is background in your world, keep it simple. Not every romantasy needs theological complexity. If your world has no gods or organised religion, adapt or skip. And if you're drawing on real religions, be thoughtful about what you're borrowing and whether your portrayal is respectful.


== Common Mistakes with Religious Worldbuilding


#mistake-box(
  title: "Mistake #1: The Convenient Religion",
  fix: [Make religious consequences real. Finding a way around should require genuine sacrifice or risk. The friendly priest who performs the forbidden marriage faces excommunication. The character who breaks a sacred vow loses their magic, their community, their place in the world. The earned resolutions in romantasy, like Xingyin's lifeforce sacrifice in #emph[Daughter of the Moon Goddess] or Reid's loss of his identity as a Chasseur in #emph[Serpent & Dove], work precisely because the characters pay a real price.],
)[
  Religious rules exist to create obstacles, but they're inconsistently applied. The church forbids their marriage, but a friendly priest marries them anyway with no consequences. Religious law gets invoked when the plot needs tension and conveniently forgotten when it doesn't. Or worse, the character is revealed to be a literal god by the final act, and the religious obstacles that drove the first half of the story simply evaporate because the protagonist now has the power to rewrite reality. If religious obstacles can be conveniently circumvented, they have no weight. Readers stop believing religion matters in your world, which means every future religious obstacle feels hollow. In the later #emph[From Blood and Ash] books, Poppy's evolution from oppressed Maiden to Primal God effectively removes the systemic obstacles the narrative spent its first book establishing. The difficult work of social reconciliation gets replaced by the literal power of a deity to reshape the world.
]


#mistake-box(
  title: "Mistake #2: The Strawman Faith",
  fix: [Make the faith sympathetic even when it creates obstacles. Good people should believe it for understandable reasons. The priest who opposes the union isn't cruel; they genuinely believe they're protecting the character's soul. #emph[Priory of the Orange Tree] avoids the strawman by making the Priory's mission real and urgent. The threat of the Nameless One means the vow of service isn't arbitrary. Ead's order exists for good reason, which is exactly why leaving it costs so much. Tension comes from genuinely conflicting goods, not from good versus obvious evil.],
)[
  The religion that creates obstacles is obviously corrupt, cruel, or foolish. The only devout characters are villains or fools. The faith exists solely to be wrong so the protagonist can be right for defying it. If the religion is clearly wrong, choosing love over faith is obviously correct. There's no internal conflict needed. The reader never doubts what the character should do, which means the choice carries no tension.
]


#mistake-box(
  title: "Mistake #3: The Painless Faith Departure",
  fix: [Show the cost of losing faith. The prayers that no longer comfort. The community that turns away. The hollow feeling where certainty used to be. In #emph[Serpent & Dove], Reid doesn't simply stop believing. His entire sense of self shatters when he discovers that the Archbishop uses scripture as a tool for punishment rather than salvation, and that he himself is the son of a witch. His crisis is a gradual, agonising process of discovery, not a clean break. Make the choice hard enough that choosing love anyway means something.],
)[
  A character raised in deep faith abandons it easily once love appears. Their entire belief system dissolves without grief or struggle. They walk away from their religion as if shrugging off a coat. Faith isn't just rules. It's identity, community, and worldview. Losing it should hurt. If it doesn't, the faith was never real, which means the obstacle was never real. #strong[Check your story against these three mistakes.] #emph[If you've already started building your religion, run it through this quick diagnostic. If you haven't, come back to this after you've completed the exercises below.] | Mistake | Could This Apply to Your Story? | How You'd Fix It | |---------|-------------------------------|-----------------| | #emph[The Convenient Religion — religious rules exist but are bypassed without real cost] | #emph[Yes — I have a "friendly priest" figure who helps them get around the marriage ban, and I haven't thought about what that costs the priest] | #emph[Give the priest real consequences for helping: excommunication, loss of community, personal guilt] | | The Convenient Religion — religious rules exist but are bypassed without real cost | | | | The Strawman Faith — the religion is obviously corrupt and no reasonable person would believe it | | | | The Painless Faith Departure — a character abandons deep faith without grief or struggle | | |
]


== The Divine: Gods & Powers


The first thing you have to decide is if there are higher powers in your world and if they are true.


The implications for your romance will be huge. If gods are confirmed and active, then "faith" isn't really faith anymore - it's recognition of fact. Characters will not be able to question whether miracles occur when miracles occur all the time. If gods are undetermined or absent, then characters may struggle with whether they believe at all, or if they just obey. And as far as the love story goes, this determines if defying the laws of the divine will result in the anger of a real being who may seek retaliation, or if breaking from tradition has no supernatural enforcement.


How you define your theological structure creates the potential for various types of stories. With multiple gods available, characters can seek patronage from individual gods, use the deities against one another, or serve different masters. A world with one god provides clearer moral stakes but leaves less room for religious diversity.


When you're writing devout characters, show faith through habit, not declaration. A devout character touches their holy symbol before danger, whispers a prayer when frightened, calls upon the name of their god while taking an oath. As a result of their faith, the way characters view events changes - that timely rescue did not occur by chance, it was providence. You don't need to explain the theology; let your characters live it. When writing characters of different faiths interacting, let their assumptions collide in small ways. Different words for good fortune. Different gestures of respect. Different things that feel sacred or profane. A person's faith will become evident in the things they're unwilling to do, what they're willing to sacrifice, and what comforts them when everything else fails.


#workbook-table(
  headers: ("Type", "How It Works", "Story Implications"),
  rows: (
    ([Monotheism], [One supreme deity], [Clear moral law; heresy feels absolute; questioning the faith means questioning everything]),
    ([Polytheism], [Multiple gods with different domains], [Gods can conflict; characters choose patrons; divine politics mirrors mortal politics]),
    ([Dualism], [Two opposing forces (good/evil, order/chaos)], [Cosmic war; sides must be chosen; grey areas feel transgressive]),
    ([Animism], [Spirits in nature, ancestors, places], [Local sacred sites; honouring the dead; magic tied to specific locations]),
    ([Confirmed gods], [Deities actively manifest and intervene], [Faith isn't faith anymore; divine will is knowable]),
    ([Absent gods], [Gods existed once but are gone/silent], [Seeking lost divinity; old rituals with uncertain power; hope or despair]),
    ([Ambiguous], [Faith without proof; gods may or may not exist], [Room for genuine doubt; faith as choice; religious and secular worldviews can coexist]),
    ([Atheistic], [No gods; religion is cultural/social], [Focus on community and tradition; meaning is human-made]),
  ),
)


#strong[Which theological system describes your world, and how does it shape what faith means for your characters?]


You can combine types (e.g., polytheism with confirmed gods, or animism with absent gods). Your choice shapes what religious doubt, devotion, and defiance look like in your story.


