== Religious Law, Doctrine & Forbidden Love

What are the actual restrictions of faith on love and marriage? Faith takes what was once an abstract idea and makes it a very real barrier. At this point, the will of God has turned into the law that prohibits your character from doing something, or requires them to do something.

This is probably the most romantic way that religious law can be used in a romantasy. The protagonists' love isn't just prohibited by religious law, but is considered heresy, or blasphemous, or an existential threat to their world. In #emph[Serpent & Dove], the Church views Lou as a "monster" inherently. In #emph[From Blood and Ash], the state religion deifies Poppy and isolates her completely. In #emph[The Jasmine Throne], the faith of the empire requires all female nobility to burn alive for "purity." These are not minor prohibitions. They are the systems by which society operates, and so the couple's romance feels like a rebellion against the universe.

