=== The Belief Change Arc


When your protagonist falls for a "heretic," their belief shifts through a recognisable progression. Understanding these stages helps you pace the internal conflict so it doesn't read as superficial or cheap. The author of #emph[Serpent & Dove] has described this as the central craft challenge of writing Reid's arc: making his de-indoctrination believable within romance beats.


#workbook-table(
  headers: ("Stage", "What Happens", "What It Feels Like"),
  rows: (
    ([#strong[Doctrinal certainty]], [The protagonist fully believes what they've been taught. The beloved's kind are monsters, demons, evil by nature.], [Safety. The world makes sense. Categories are clear.]),
    ([#strong[Embodied contradiction]], [Attraction, proximity, or intimacy creates sensory counter-evidence that doesn't fit the doctrine.], [Confusion. The doctrine says one thing; the body and heart say another.]),
    ([#strong[Epistemic crisis]], [A revelation forces the protagonist to question not just this relationship but everything they've been taught.], [Vertigo. If this was a lie, what else was? The ground dissolves.]),
    ([#strong[Reclassification]], [The protagonist revises their moral categories, either by redeeming the beloved or redefining what "evil" means.], [Loss and liberation. The old world is gone. A new one must be built.]),
  ),
)


