=== Conversion & Religious Identity


When a character converts for love, changing faith, species, or worldview to be with their partner, the consequences are much greater than those of outside obstacles. Converting is about more than just adding a different label to your identity. It means rebuilding yourself. And in romantasy, this can literally occur: the human becomes a vampire, the mortal becomes a Fae, the priestess renounces her vows.


The difference lies between a genuine conversion and a hollow one. Genuine conversions involve a real transformation of how the character views themselves. They don't just change what they practice; they change how they see themselves and their purpose in life. In #emph[From Sand and Ash], Angelo's conversion from a Catholic priest to a man who will do anything to be with Eva is not portrayed as a rejection of his faith, but as the realisation of his true purpose, which is validated through great sacrifice. Hollow conversions are done for the sake of expediency. The character will follow the procedures required to fulfil a legal or social obligation, however, there will be no real change in their perceptions of themselves. If a character "converts" to the rituals of a new culture merely to fit in with a partner, without the story showing the inner conflict the character experienced, the conversion will feel empty.


Another aspect to consider is guilt. The partner responsible for the conversion will have to carry the weight of having destroyed a part of the person they love - their heritage, their community, their connection to family and traditions. This guilt can be used as another source of romantic tension.


And perhaps the greatest subversion is the character who chooses not to convert. Miryem in #emph[Spinning Silver] does not choose to assimilate into the cold world of the Staryk King, even though it would provide her with both wealth and influence. Instead, her decision to not conform to his expectations is what gives her a happy romantic ending. The most authentic conclusion is one where the character's original identity is respected and incorporated, not rejected.


#strong[Does either character change faith, species, or worldview to be with their partner?]


Conversion for love raises questions about authenticity, sacrifice, and identity.


